<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="410">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181866" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole dryas Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole dryas Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dryas">Pheidole dryas</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="410">Types INBio.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="410">Etymology L, Gr Dryas, in classical mythology, a wood nymph whose life was that of her tree, referring to the arboricolous nesting habit of the species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="410">Diagnosis A unique medium-sized, yellowish brown species whose major has a heart-shaped head, when mandibles are included, in full-face view; all of the dorsal head surface, including the clypeus but excluding the occiput, densely covered by longitudinal carinulae; conspicuously swollen hind femur; and angulate subpostpetiolar process.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="410">
There is some similarity to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181870" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole erratilis Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole erratilis Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erratilis">erratilis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181912" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole nitella Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole nitella Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitella">nitella</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181926" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole pygmaea Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole pygmaea Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">pygmaea</taxonomicName>
, but many differences in body form, sculpturing, and color. Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.94, HL 1.02, SL 0.46, EL 0.10, PW 0.54. Paratype minor: HW 0.50, HL 0.56, SL 0.42, EL 0.06, PW 0.34.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="410">color Major: gaster light yellowish brown, rest of body and appendages dark yellow. Minor: concolorous light yellowish brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="410">Range Atlantic slope of Cordillera Central, Costa Rica (Longino 1997).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="410">Biology The type series, representing either one or several colonies, was found in mature wet forest under epiphyte mats in a canopy tree (Longino 1997).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
